	<h3>Understanding the Front Setback Line</h3>
	<p>The front setback line determines where height limits change:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Front setback line:</strong> Imaginary line extending from front of house to property sides</li>
		<li><strong>In front of line:</strong> 42-inch maximum height (front yard rules apply)</li>
		<li><strong>Behind line:</strong> 72-inch maximum height (backyard rules apply)</li>
		<li><strong>Corner lots:</strong> May have two front setback lines (more restrictive)</li>
		<li><strong>Irregular lots:</strong> May require survey to determine setback accurately</li>
		<li><strong>Varies by zoning:</strong> Commercial and agricultural zones have different rules</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>When You Can Build Taller Than Standard Limits</h3>
	<p>Options for exceeding normal height restrictions:</p>

	<p><strong>Variance Application:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>When needed:</strong> Fences exceeding standard height limits</li>
		<li><strong>Application process:</strong> Submit to Planning Department with justification</li>
		<li><strong>Cost:</strong> $350-650 application fee</li>
		<li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 6-12 weeks for approval/denial</li>
		<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> Demonstrate hardship or special circumstances</li>
		<li><strong>Success rate:</strong> Varies; privacy alone often insufficient justification</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Valid Variance Justifications:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Property adjacent to commercial area requiring noise/visual buffer</li>
		<li>Lot backs to highway or major road with safety/noise concerns</li>
		<li>Topography creates special circumstances (elevated neighbors overlooking)</li>
		<li>Security requirements for business or special-use property</li>
		<li>Pool safety enclosure requirements exceeding standard height</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>HOA Restrictions May Be More Strict</h3>
	<p>Homeowner associations often impose additional limitations:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Height limits:</strong> May restrict to 5 feet even in backyard</li>
		<li><strong>Style requirements:</strong> Specific materials, colors, designs mandated</li>
		<li><strong>Approval process:</strong> Architectural review required before installation</li>
		<li><strong>Front yard rules:</strong> May prohibit fencing entirely in some communities</li>
		<li><strong>Enforcement:</strong> HOA can require removal of non-compliant fencing</li>
		<li><strong>Always check first:</strong> Review CC&Rs before planning fence</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Privacy Effectiveness by Height</h2>

	<h3>How Different Heights Perform</h3>
	<p>Real-world privacy levels at common fence heights:</p>

	<p><strong>4-Foot Fence Privacy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Standing privacy:</strong> None - average adult easily sees over</li>
		<li><strong>Sitting privacy:</strong> Good for patio seating, deck furniture</li>
		<li><strong>Pet containment:</strong> Adequate for small dogs, insufficient for large dogs</li>
		<li><strong>Visual barrier:</strong> Minimal - neighbors clearly visible</li>
		<li><strong>Noise reduction:</strong> Negligible sound blocking</li>
		<li><strong>Best use:</strong> Decorative boundaries, front yards, defining spaces</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>5-Foot Fence Privacy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Standing privacy:</strong> Partial - blocks view to shoulder height</li>
		<li><strong>Sitting privacy:</strong> Excellent for most outdoor activities</li>
		<li><strong>Pet containment:</strong> Good for most medium-sized dogs</li>
		<li><strong>Visual barrier:</strong> Moderate - significant screening but not complete</li>
		<li><strong>Noise reduction:</strong> Slight reduction in ambient noise</li>
		<li><strong>Best use:</strong> Compromise height when regulations prevent 6-foot</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>6-Foot Fence Privacy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Standing privacy:</strong> Excellent - blocks view for average height adults</li>
		<li><strong>Sitting privacy:</strong> Complete privacy for all ground-level activities</li>
		<li><strong>Pet containment:</strong> Excellent for all but jumping breeds</li>
		<li><strong>Visual barrier:</strong> Comprehensive - neighbors not visible in most situations</li>
		<li><strong>Noise reduction:</strong> Moderate reduction (20-30% sound blocking)</li>
		<li><strong>Best use:</strong> Standard backyard privacy fence, most common choice</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>8-Foot Fence Privacy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Standing privacy:</strong> Maximum - complete visual privacy</li>
		<li><strong>Sitting privacy:</strong> Absolute privacy regardless of seating</li>
		<li><strong>Pet containment:</strong> Maximum security for even athletic dogs</li>
		<li><strong>Visual barrier:</strong> Total - creates complete enclosure feel</li>
		<li><strong>Noise reduction:</strong> Significant reduction (30-40% sound blocking)</li>
		<li><strong>Best use:</strong> Special privacy needs, adjacent to tall structures</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Accounting for Ground Level Differences</h3>
	<p>Elevation changes dramatically affect privacy effectiveness:</p>

	<p><strong>Your Property is Lower:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Problem:</strong> Neighbors look down into your yard over fence</li>
		<li><strong>Solution:</strong> Add 1-2 feet to standard height to compensate</li>
		<li><strong>Example:</strong> 2-foot grade difference may require 8-foot fence for 6-foot privacy</li>
		<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> Measure from neighbor's ground level, not yours</li>
		<li><strong>Permit consideration:</strong> May need variance for extra height</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Your Property is Higher:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Standard height fence provides extra privacy</li>
		<li><strong>Consideration:</strong> Fence appears much taller to neighbors (be considerate)</li>
		<li><strong>Example:</strong> 6-foot fence on 2-foot elevation looks 8-foot from neighbor side</li>
		<li><strong>Neighbor relations:</strong> Discuss plans to avoid conflicts</li>
		<li><strong>Aesthetic option:</strong> May be able to use shorter fence and still achieve privacy</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Sloped Yards:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Stepped design:</strong> Fence follows grade in level sections</li>
		<li><strong>Racked design:</strong> Fence panels angle to follow slope</li>
		<li><strong>Height measurement:</strong> Measured from ground at each post location</li>
		<li><strong>Privacy gaps:</strong> Sloped yards may have privacy gaps at high points</li>
		<li><strong>Solution:</strong> Increase overall height to maintain minimum privacy at highest points</li>
	</ul>

